The Harren Charter is one of several dozen frontier grants issued during the Lantern Reforms period, all following the same template: private authority, registry obligation, revenue sharing, charter review. The template was administratively cheap: Midgaard gained governance reach without deploying administrative staff. Charter review — suspension of rights during registry gaps — replaced direct administrative oversight. In practice, charter review was rarely invoked: frontier houses maintained registries because revenue rights depended on them, creating self-enforcing compliance. The burial lease tribunal ruling established that chartered authority superseded pre-charter customary rights, becoming a model for subsequent charters in areas with contested prior use. Midgaard's Continuity faction cites the ruling as correct charter law; the Reckoning faction cites it as an example of charter law extinguishing rights that predate the charter system entirely.

