Kowloon's Courier Lantern Office maintains records of passage-tax payments from Harren Charter territory. The passage tax adds cost to northern timber and ore shipments; the Harbor Syndics have formally complained twice about the Harren Charter's tax rate relative to road maintenance provided. Both complaints were resolved by Midgaard's tribunal in Harren's favor. Kowloon has since routed some northern freight through alternative paths to avoid the passage tax, adding travel time but removing the tax obligation. The routing shift has reduced Harren Charter passage revenue and is the subject of an ongoing dispute in which Harren claims the alternative routes were specifically developed to circumvent the charter. Kowloon views the Harren Charter as an example of how frontier grants create private revenue bottlenecks against public routing efficiency.

