Mafdet's Ledger Houses have no jurisdiction over inland frontier grants and no formal position on the Harren Charter. The passage taxation model has a maritime analogue in Mafdet's harbor tariff system — private authority over a chokepoint, public registry obligation, revenue sharing with the overseeing institution. The analogue ends at the burial lease: maritime law has no equivalent to charging fees for access to graves. The Swift Court's standard cargo contract includes a clause exempting maritime cargo from inland passage taxes where alternative sea routes exist — a provision partly motivated by early experience with Harren-style toll structures on overland freight.

