Khenari communities use the Thornwood-adjacent territory for seasonal burial practices predating the Harren Charter by multiple generations. Khenari burial doctrine treats undocumented burial sites as sacred gaps — spaces whose significance derives precisely from not being formally registered in any human-maintained ledger system. The Harren Charter's burial lease imposed fees on leased burial ground; Khenari burial practice avoids the registered ground specifically because registry contact changes the nature of the sacred gap. House Harren's attempts to expand the registry to include all burial activity have been unsuccessful at finding Khenari burial sites, because the sites are defined by their absence from Harren's documentation. Nine descents of Khenari seasonal burial practice in the Thornwood predate the charter; the community's oral tradition records each descent's specific locations in terms that do not correspond to Harren's survey coordinates. The Harren Charter tribunal ruling established that registered burial ground was subject to charter authority; it said nothing about unregistered ground. The gap remains.
